<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>T 444E Diesel Engine Diagnostics (1997) - SECTION 4: SUPPLEMENTAL DIAGNOSTIC ANALYSIS - COOLANT IN LUBE OIL
        - PROCEDURES
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="proctype" graphiccount="3">
        <title>PROCEDURES</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Plug in block heater to warm coolant.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove oil pan plug, oil filter and glow plugs.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Pressurize cooling system to 14 PSI.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Observe/inspect rear of oil cooler (where oil filter was mounted),
                <emph type="bold">(Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef1252006">4.6</hotlnk>)
                </emph>
                oil pan plug for coolant or air pressure escaping.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If: Coolant/air leak is occurring from header at the oil filter mounting header the oil
                cooler assembly should be removed and inspected or pressure tested.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If the coolant is escaping out of the oil pan drain plug remove valve covers, inspect the
                cylinder head area
                <emph type="bold">(Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef1252007">4.7</hotlnk>)
                </emph>
                under the valve cover and welch plugs in cylinder heads for coolant leakage.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If no leaks are found remove engine and oil pan, block off coolant inlet, outlet and heater
                hose connections. Pressurize the cooling system with 14 PSI of regulated air pressure.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect bottom end of crankcase for pressure leaks.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If no leaks found, remove front cover and inspect gaskets and sealing surfaces (
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef1252008">4.8</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                ).
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Re-test after repair to confirm repair.</para>
            <figure id="ef1252006" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="eg7139" filename="../figeg7/EG7139.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 4.6 Oil Cooler Leak Paths</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="ef1252007" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="eg7140" filename="../figeg7/EG7140.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 4.7 Cylinder Head Welch Plug Coolant Leak Paths</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="ef1252008" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="eg7141" filename="../figeg7/EG7141.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 4.8 Front Cover Coolant Leak Paths</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
